# Task Management System

## Folder Structure

```
Tasks/
  Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md    # One file per week, named by Monday's date (e.g. Weekly-wc-16-Mar-2026.md)
  Daily-Tasks.md              # Single file — always overwritten at start of each day
  Completed/
    Week-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md    # One file per week — top-level one-liners only
```

---

## Trigger Phrases

| Phrase | Action |
|---|---|
| "Start of day" / "morning tasks" | Run **Start of Day** workflow |
| "End of day" / "day done" | Run **End of Day** workflow |
| "Start of week" / "weekly review" | Run **Start of Week** workflow |
| "End of week" / "week done" | Run **End of Week** workflow |

---

## File Formats

### Weekly File — `Tasks/Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md`

```markdown
# Week commencing DD MMM YYYY — Mon DD MMM to Fri DD MMM YYYY

## Outstanding from Last Week
1. [ ] Task carried forward
2. [ ] Task carried forward

## Monday DD MMM
1. [ ] Task
2. [ ] Task

## Tuesday DD MMM — NOMOS DAY
1. [ ] Nomos task
2. [ ] Nomos task

## Wednesday DD MMM
1. [ ] Task

## Thursday DD MMM
1. [ ] Task

## Friday DD MMM
1. [ ] Task

## Ongoing
1. [ ] Ongoing responsibility or project

## Key Dates This Week
- DD MMM — Event or deadline
```

- All tasks must use numbered lists — never bullet points.
- Mark tasks complete with `[x]` as they are confirmed done.
- A task is only marked `[x]` when Matt confirms it.

### Daily File — `Tasks/Daily-Tasks.md`

```markdown
# Daily Tasks — DAY DD MMM YYYY

## From Weekly Plan
1. [ ] Task pulled from this week's file
2. [ ] Task pulled from this week's file

## Additional Today
1. [ ] Any task added at start of day

## Completed Today
1. [x] Task confirmed done
```

- This file is **always overwritten** at the start of each new day.
- All tasks must use numbered lists — never bullet points.
- At end of day, completed items move to the "Completed Today" section.

### Completed Archive — `Tasks/Completed/Week-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md`

```markdown
# Week commencing DD MMM YYYY

1. Task one-liner
2. Task one-liner
3. Task one-liner
```

- **No detail.** One line per completed task, maximum.
- Numbered list only.
- Appended to at end of week from the weekly file's completed tasks.

---

## Workflows

### Start of Week

1. Read all files in `Tasks/` and `Marketing/`, `Operations/`, `Hubspot/`, `Nomos/` for context on outstanding items.
2. Identify any incomplete tasks from the previous weekly file.
3. Create `Tasks/Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md` with tasks organised by day, all in numbered lists:
   - Outstanding carried-forward tasks
   - Tasks assigned to specific days
   - Nomos tasks on Tuesday only
   - Ongoing responsibilities
   - Key dates (check campaign files, plans, and any dated documents)
4. Ask Matt yes/no confirmation questions to catch anything missed:
   - "Do you have any meetings or deadlines this week not already listed?"
   - "Are there any campaigns or projects needing action this week?"
   - "Anything outstanding from last week I may have missed?"

### Start of Day

1. Read the current `Tasks/Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md`.
2. Read the previous `Tasks/Daily-Tasks.md` to check for anything incomplete yesterday.
3. Overwrite `Tasks/Daily-Tasks.md` with today's tasks in a numbered list drawn from the weekly plan.
4. Ask Matt yes/no questions to catch anything extra:
   - "Any calls or meetings today not already listed?"
   - "Anything urgent that's come up since yesterday?"
   - "Any tasks from yesterday not completed that need to carry forward?"

### End of Day

1. Go through each task one by one — ask Matt yes/no per task.
2. Update `Tasks/Daily-Tasks.md` — mark confirmed completed items `[x]`.
3. Update `Tasks/Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md` — mark any weekly tasks fully done `[x]`.
4. Ask:
   - "Is there anything not on the list that you completed today?"
   - "Anything to carry forward to tomorrow?"
   - "Any new tasks that have come up for later in the week?"

### End of Week

1. Read `Tasks/Weekly-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md` — identify all completed and incomplete tasks.
2. Go through unconfirmed items one by one — ask Matt yes/no per task.
3. Create or append to `Tasks/Completed/Week-wc-DD-Mon-YYYY.md` — one-liner per completed task, numbered list only.
4. Carry any incomplete tasks into the next week's file.
5. Ask:
   - "Any tasks completed this week not already marked?"
   - "Anything to carry into next week?"
   - "Any key dates next week I should note?"

---

## Rules

1. All tasks must always be in a **numbered list** — never bullet points.
2. When displaying any task list in chat, every single task must be on its own line with a blank line between each item to ensure vertical spacing. Never run tasks together on the same line.
3. Always ask questions after any trigger — never assume tasks are complete without confirmation.
4. Keep questions binary (yes/no) wherever possible to reduce friction.
5. Never add detail to the `Completed/` archive files — one line per task, numbered list only.
6. `Daily-Tasks.md` is always overwritten — it represents only the current day.
7. The weekly file is the source of truth for the week.
8. Key dates must always be surfaced at the start of each week and day where relevant.
9. Matt will always state the day of the week when triggering a workflow. Use this to determine which tasks are relevant.
10. All dev requests go to Michael — Matt never contacts the dev team directly.
11. **Never add tasks to any task file without Matt explicitly asking for them to be added.** If something seems worth adding, ask first — do not add it unilaterally.

## Day-Specific Rules

### Every Morning — Publer Check
- Remind Matt to check Publer every morning to ensure all posts for that day are planned, scheduled and have no issues.
- Include this as the first item in every daily task list.

### Tuesday — Nomos Day
- All Nomos-related work is scheduled exclusively on Tuesdays.
- On any other day, do not include Nomos tasks in the daily task list.
- At the start of each Tuesday, pull all outstanding Nomos tasks into the daily list.
- At start of week, Nomos tasks are listed under Tuesday in the weekly file.
